uilding a Soviet world? Based on years of research in the former Soviet Union, Bruce Grant's book draws upon Nivkh interviews, newly opened archives, and rarely translated Soviet ethnographic texts to examine the effects of this remarkable state venture in the construction of identity. With a keen sensitivity, Grant explores the often paradoxical participation by Nivkhi in these shifting waves of Sovietization and poses questions about how cultural identity is constituted and reconstituted, restructured and dismantled. Part chronicle of modernization, part saga of memory and forgetting, In the Soviet House of Culture is an interpretive ethnography of one people's attempts to recapture the past as they look toward the future. This is a book that will appeal to anthropologists and historians alike, as well as to anyone who is interested in the people and politics of the former Soviet Union.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEthnologyzRussia (Federation)zSakhalin (Sakhalinskai︠a︡ oblastʹ). 0aGilyaks. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAdo-Tymovo.  aAleksandrovsk.  aBattleship Potemkin.  aBenjamin, Walter.  aBrezhnev, Leonid.  aChaivo.  aChir-Unvd.  aChurka, Aleksei.  aCommittee of the North.  aDostoevskii, Fedor.  aDown with Illiteracy Society.  aEngels, Frederick.  aEvenki.  aFar Eastern Republic.  aGorbachev, Mikhail.  aHawes, Charles.  aHumphrey, Caroline.  aIuzhno-Sakhalinsk.  aKarafuto.  aKhrushchev, Nikita.  aKreinovich, Erukhim A.  aLazarev.  aManchuria.  aMarx, Karl.  aNanaitsy.  aNekrasovka.  aNogliki.  aOkha.  aPakskun, Grigorii.  aPogibi.  aRomanovka.  aRybnoe.  aRybnovsk.  aSoldiers of Culture.  aTengi.  aUdegeitsy.  aVereshchagino.  aculture bases.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton Univer